#!/usr/bin/env bash
# fedora-bootstrap — orchestrator. Run as ROOT on a fresh host (Day 0).
# Version: 1.2.29 (live-gate-cadence: the live-gate watcher now polls every 15s (was 5min) for snappy turn-around during active development — live-gate-watch.timer OnBootSec/OnUnitActiveSec=15s + AccuracySec=1s (REQUIRED for systemd to honor a sub-minute interval; default accuracy batches to ~1min) + the RandomizedDelaySec jitter dropped. Safe at 15s: the watcher self-serializes via flock, so while a build runs the intervening firings skip instantly; an idle firing is a cheap distrobox-enter + one `gh pr list` (well under rate limits). The build+gate (~90s+) dominates total turn, so 15s is mostly pickup latency. No other change. Prior: v1.2.28 (live-gate-fix: two robustness fixes to the v1.2.27 transport, both PROVEN. (1) The watcher runs IN the claudebox: live-gate-watch.service ExecStart now `distrobox enter claudebox -- bash -lc ...` because gh + git are CLAUDEBOX tools, NOT on the minimal host — the watcher polls gh + drives the host podman engine via the box's CONTAINER_HOST bridge (build/run still land on the HOST engine). Without this the host systemd --user service failed `gh pr list` (no gh on host) and gated nothing. (2) Setup's workload-clone update no longer ABORTS on a dirty working tree: ~/<name> is a SETUP-MANAGED clone (the loop tooling fetches PR refs + git-archives, never authoritatively edits it), so the update now discards stray working-tree changes (git reset --hard HEAD + git clean -fd) then `git merge --ff-only origin/main` — preserving the force-push detection the old `git pull --ff-only` had (a blind `reset --hard origin/main` would SILENTLY accept a force-push to main; this still surfaces it). Prior: v1.2.27 (live-gate-loop: closes the pre-merge autonomous-loop TRANSPORT. Adds live-gate-run.sh (gate ONE PR: build the candidate disposably via build-candidate.sh -> validate-candidate.sh Gate B -> `gh pr comment` the GREEN/RED verdict; the host COMMENTS, never merges) + live-gate-watch.sh (a systemd --user timer that polls `live-validate`-labelled workload PRs, dedups per-commit via ~/.local/state/live-gate/<wl>-<sha>.done, invokes the runner) + per-workload presets (live-gate-presets/<wl>.env -> ~/.config/live-gate/; host fallback, a workload may ship its own `.live-gate`). The gate runs a DISPOSABLE container that never touches the running workload, so it is NOT gated on the dev session — validation runs WHILE fedora-dev is in active use (the loop's whole point). PROVEN end-to-end: a `live-validate`-labelled fedora-dev test PR was built-from-source + gated GREEN on the host and the verdict posted back to the PR; the watcher discovered the labelled PR and deduped. Closes the loop: fedora-dev opens/labels a PR -> host builds+gates+verdicts -> fedora-dev iterates (RED) or Arthur merges (GREEN), human at exactly one point. setup-user.sh installs the two scripts + presets + units and enables live-gate-watch.timer. Prior: v1.2.26 (live-gate-builder: adds build-candidate.sh — the host's pre-merge BUILD step, the linchpin of the live-gate loop. Given a workload clone + an optional PR ref, it exports the ref to a THROWAWAY source tree (git archive -> mktemp, no clone mutation), podman builds a DISPOSABLE candidate (localhost/disposable/<name>:val-<sha>; default isolation works on the host's native-overlay top-level engine — no --isolation=chroot, unlike the nested dev box), hands the local image to validate-candidate.sh (Gate B: --rm fenced run + access-probe), then rmi's the candidate (base layers stay cached for the next churn). PROVEN end-to-end: the host built fedora-dev from source + gated it GREEN — the pre-merge build->gate path that CI (no PR publish) and the dev box (cannot live-run PID-1) cannot do. setup-user.sh now installs build-candidate.sh AND validate-candidate.sh (the latter was previously an uninstalled orphan). Sanctioned by the v1.2.25 carve-out: never pushed, never a WORKLOAD_CONTAINERS member, never in the deploy path. Prior: v1.2.25 (policy-carveout: amends the host law to PERMIT disposable host validation builds. policy/CLAUDE.md (+ project CLAUDE.md) now split "build a SHIPPING image" (always CI, never on the host) from "build a THROWAWAY validation image" (PERMITTED, pre-merge live-gate only): the host MAY podman build a candidate SOLELY to live-test an open PR before merge — required because CI publishes nothing pullable on an open PR (build.yml push:false on pull_request) and the dev box's nested engine cannot live-run a PID-1 image, so the host is the ONLY surface that yields a faithful pre-merge verdict. Permitted ONLY when localhost/disposable-namespaced (never a ghcr deploy ref), never podman push'd (the host holds no write:packages credential), run --rm + rmi'd on teardown, and never a WORKLOAD_CONTAINERS member. This is exactly what validation/rollback-spike.sh already does — the flat "never podman build" law had silently forbidden it. Shipping images stay CI-only + cosign-signed; the deploy path is UNCHANGED. Enables the pre-merge live-gate loop (the host candidate-builder is the next, non-control-plane step). Prior: v1.2.24 (default-effort: the host claudebox now STARTS every session at maximum effort. The `claude` wrapper (setup-user.sh) injects --settings {"ultracode":true} so each session begins in ultracode (= xhigh effort + workflow-by-default); ultracode is SESSION-SCOPED and IGNORED in settings files, so the wrapper is the only place it can be made a default. policy/managed-settings.json also gains top-level "effortLevel":"xhigh" as the persistent floor for any non-wrapper path (subagents, direct /usr/bin/claude). With v1.2.20's defaultMode:auto this COMPLETES the autonomous-defaults set: a fresh setup.sh re-run brings the box up in auto mode at ultracode with no per-session action. MERGE GATE UNCHANGED — the gate-push.sh ask hook, the git push / gh pr merge deny rules, and disableBypassPermissionsMode all remain. Prior: v1.2.23 loop-gate-B: parameterized validate-candidate.sh (the pre-merge LIVE gate) with CAND_FENCE (the candidate's run-contract caps/devices, minus public ports + real secrets; default = hardest untrusted fence) + CAND_PROBE (the workload's "does it serve" assertion, run on the candidate's OWN loopback via podman exec). Proven faithful: a correctly-serving candidate PASSES; a candidate that is healthy/up but serves wrong (HTTP 500) is caught by the probe and FAILS — the access-path probe is load-bearing, not just the healthcheck. Validation tooling; no production behavior change. Prior: v1.2.22 loop-gate-A: proved container-refresh.sh's never-fired ROLLBACK branch GREEN via validation/rollback-spike.sh — a bad :latest that won't go healthy is retagged to the prior digest, restarted, and recovers with a .rolled-back marker. Two fixes it required: an explicit HealthCmd in the spike's throwaway Quadlet (OCI drops a built image's HEALTHCHECK) + a new BUSY_PROBE seam in container-refresh.sh (UNSET in production = the claudebox probe unchanged; a non-claudebox workload sets BUSY_PROBE=/bin/true, the documented empty-probe path). No production behavior change. Prior: v1.2.21 policy-fix: setup-user.sh wrote the image-trust policy.json "containers-storage" transport as a bare ARRAY instead of a scope->requirements OBJECT; containers-image rejected the WHOLE policy ("JSON object expected, got 91") so EVERY ghcr.io/oso-gato pull failed and no workload could start (fedora-dev stuck restart-looping). Fixed both writers (create-heredoc + merge), the idempotent merge now REPAIRS an already-broken host in place, and a fail-closed structural check rejects any non-object transport. Prior: v1.2.20 auto-mode: the host claudebox now DEFAULTS to the 'auto' permission mode — policy/managed-settings.json drops "disableAutoMode":"disable" and adds "defaultMode":"auto", so in-box sessions start without routine permission prompts (a background classifier still vets each action). The MERGE GATE IS UNCHANGED: the managed gate-push.sh 'ask' hook, the git push / gh pr merge deny rules, and disableBypassPermissionsMode all remain, so nothing reaches main without explicit approval. Prior: v1.2.19 policy: the host image-trust policy.json now also permits the class-(a) Fedora base registry.fedoraproject.org/fedora plus the containers-storage transport (local save/load), so the validation/ host-validation spikes+gates can pull stock Fedora fixtures into a throwaway tar cache. Production run-set UNCHANGED — workload Quadlets reference only ghcr.io/oso-gato/*, default stays reject, the docker "" fallback stays reject; this widens only what may be PULLED for disposable host-validation, not what RUNS. setup-user.sh writes it fresh (heredoc) and idempotently/additively merges the two entries into an existing policy.json without clobbering operator edits. Same insecureAcceptAnything posture as the oso-gato stanza; both upgradeable to sigstoreSigned in lockstep later. Prior: v1.2.18 tmux SINGLE-GROUP multi-client geometry-race fix; v1.2.17 FLEET.md swarm map; v1.2.16 Day-0 wizard (day0.sh asks for the TS auth key); v1.2.15 spin-up path explicit; v1.2.14 day-0 TS_AUTHKEY prompt; v1.2.13 docs cleanup; v1.2.12 FLEET governance (3-box model, host PR-only, fedora-dev sole merge box); v1.2.11 BUILT promotion gate; v1.2.10 HEADLESS prerequisite; v1.2.9 Principle 3 MINIMAL; v1.2.8 Principle 2(c); v1.2.7 PR-first maintainership; v1.2.5 verify.sh fail2ban euid-gate fix; v1.2.4 genesis/mother-platform role + fedora-dev maintainership.)
#
# Runs the two privilege layers in their correct identities (see README "Privilege layers"):
#   setup-host.sh  — the SYSTEM layer, as ROOT: host packages, /etc, system services, the
#                    tailnet node, and CREATES the operating user + its rootless prerequisites.
#   setup-user.sh  — the ROOTLESS layer, as the operating user: user podman socket, ssh keys,
#                    claudebox, Claude policy, verify. Needs NO host privilege.
# Idempotent — re-run safely.
set -euo pipefail
HERE="$(cd "$(dirname "$0")" && pwd)"
U="${BOOTSTRAP_USER:-core}"

if [ "$(id -u)" = 0 ]; then
    BOOTSTRAP_USER="$U" "$HERE/setup-host.sh"
    # Hand off to the operating user for the rootless layer. The root phase already
    # brought up its user bus, so `su -` finds it. `< /dev/null` keeps a queued paste line
    # (e.g. a following `passwd`) from being swallowed by a child that reads stdin.
    su - "$U" -c "GH_KEYS_USER='${GH_KEYS_USER:-oso-gato}' '$HERE/setup-user.sh'" < /dev/null
else
    # Invoked as the unprivileged user: run ONLY the rootless layer. The system layer must
    # already have been provisioned as root (run setup.sh as root on a fresh host).
    echo ">> Running the rootless (user) layer only. The SYSTEM layer must already be in place;"
    echo ">> on a fresh host run setup.sh as root instead."
    exec "$HERE/setup-user.sh"
fi
